      <abstract>
        <p>Lichen sclerosus is an uncommon inflammatory dermatosis with preferential
involvement of the urogenital region. The extragenital involvement is uncommon
and is characterized by small rounded macules or papules, pearly white in color.
The coexistence of lichen sclerosus and scleroderma plaques in most cases with
extragenital location has been reported in the literature. We report a case of
lichen sclerosus associated with scleroderma in children, highlighting the
importance of dermoscopy in diagnosis.</p>
      </abstract>
